00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:01.729 align:middle line:84%
in our personal lives, all
that can be very disconcerting.

00:03:01.729 --> 00:03:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:04.145 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: We're living
in an era that's

00:03:04.145 --> 00:03:06.250 align:middle line:84%
going through such a
high-speed period of change.

00:03:06.250 --> 00:03:07.760 align:middle line:84%
Very, very stressful,
statistically

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:09.860 align:middle line:90%
it bears all that out.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:11.120 align:middle line:90%
Stress is debilitating.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:13.970 align:middle line:84%
When we experience
too much stress,

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:17.580 align:middle line:84%
it has a big impact on our
health, negative impact.

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:20.400 align:middle line:84%
It robs us of the
quality of life.

00:03:20.400 --> 00:03:22.320 align:middle line:84%
Many things come from
having too much stress.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:23.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I want to
break that down

00:03:23.140 --> 00:03:25.310 align:middle line:84%
into two different things,
two different types of stress.

00:03:25.310 --> 00:03:25.935 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Sure.

00:03:25.935 --> 00:03:27.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The stress
that comes from outside

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:30.267 align:middle line:84%
in, where people are
losing their homes,

00:03:30.267 --> 00:03:31.850 align:middle line:84%
they're being laid
off from their jobs

00:03:31.850 --> 00:03:36.680 align:middle line:84%
right before holidays, they're
experiencing an enormous amount

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.830 align:middle line:84%
because of our
economy and situations

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:40.960 align:middle line:90%
that are happening in our media.

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:44.950 align:middle line:84%
It seems to really label and
emphasize a lot of stress

00:03:44.950 --> 00:03:45.850 align:middle line:90%
for people.

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:47.070 align:middle line:90%
So that's one type of stress.

00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:48.778 align:middle line:84%
The other thing is
the chemical reactions

00:03:48.778 --> 00:03:50.960 align:middle line:84%
that happen in the body
when stress occurs--

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:53.990 align:middle line:84%
the cortisol release, the fight
or flight-- all of those things

00:03:53.990 --> 00:03:55.660 align:middle line:84%
that break the
immune system down.

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:57.550 align:middle line:84%
So there's the external
stress and then

00:03:57.550 --> 00:03:58.930 align:middle line:90%
there's the internal stress.

00:03:58.930 --> 00:03:59.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: And the
effect of stress

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:01.550 align:middle line:84%
that happens
internally in our body.

00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:04.901 align:middle line:84%
People think about the external
things as their stress--

00:04:04.901 --> 00:04:07.150 align:middle line:84%
losing the home, losing the
job, those kind of things.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:08.747 align:middle line:84%
And, yeah, those
events are stressful.

00:04:08.747 --> 00:04:09.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:10.810 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: That's a given.

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:13.470 align:middle line:84%
But researchers for
years used to do,

00:04:13.470 --> 00:04:15.890 align:middle line:84%
even the earliest research
on stress-- Hans Selye

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:19.519 align:middle line:84%
and these different people that
were doing research on stress--

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:21.370 align:middle line:84%
said that stress
was not the events,

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:22.950 align:middle line:84%
it was the perception
of the events.

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:24.824 align:middle line:84%
We were perceiving the
event in a certain way

00:04:24.824 --> 00:04:26.255 align:middle line:84%
and, therefore,
it was stressful.

00:04:26.255 --> 00:04:28.880 align:middle line:84%
What we've learned at HeartMath,
at the Institute of HeartMath,

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:30.775 align:middle line:84%
and what I've
learned personally is

00:04:30.775 --> 00:04:32.940 align:middle line:84%
it's not just the
perception of the events,

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:36.315 align:middle line:84%
it's what happens emotionally
when we have that perception.

00:04:36.315 --> 00:04:40.420 align:middle line:84%
The emotions are really where
the stress is being registered.

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:43.470 align:middle line:84%
And when we experience strong
negative emotions, like anxiety

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:46.580 align:middle line:84%
or frustration or anger or
disappointment, those kind

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:49.890 align:middle line:84%
of emotions, a lot goes on
in the body that's not good.

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:53.180 align:middle line:84%
You mentioned hormones--
it releases hormones

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:55.020 align:middle line:84%
into our system that
are not good for us

00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:56.728 align:middle line:84%
when they are there
in excessive amounts.

00:04:56.728 --> 00:04:59.670 align:middle line:84%
No hormone is bad, but it's
about the hormone relationships

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:01.190 align:middle line:90%
and balances.

00:05:01.190 --> 00:05:02.830 align:middle line:90%
Too much cortisol, for example.

00:05:02.830 --> 00:05:05.270 align:middle line:84%
Cortisol is generically
known as the stress hormone--

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:05.890 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Stress
hormone, right, uh-huh.

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:07.889 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Too much cortisol
does a lot of things

00:05:07.889 --> 00:05:09.469 align:middle line:84%
to our physical
body we don't want.

00:05:09.469 --> 00:05:11.010 align:middle line:84%
Too much adrenaline--
the same thing.

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:13.218 align:middle line:84%
And these are both hormones
that are directly related

00:05:13.218 --> 00:05:15.520 align:middle line:90%
to the stress response.

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:18.660 align:middle line:84%
To understand how to
better regulate stress,

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:21.500 align:middle line:84%
we have to learn how to better
regulate emotional responses.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:22.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:27.330 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: So to manage the
stress response to that is not

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:29.080 align:middle line:84%
as much important
to say we're not

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:30.760 align:middle line:84%
going to have those
feelings; it's

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:32.510 align:middle line:84%
what do we do with
them when we have them.

00:05:32.510 --> 00:05:35.020 align:middle line:84%
How fast can we move
out of those emotions

00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:38.050 align:middle line:84%
into something that's
at least neutralized

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:41.610 align:middle line:84%
those negative feelings or
possibly transformed them

00:05:41.610 --> 00:05:44.930 align:middle line:84%
into something else that's
regenerative and positive.

00:05:44.930 --> 00:05:46.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And one
of the big topics

00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:48.595 align:middle line:84%
we're going to be talking
about today is resilience

00:05:48.595 --> 00:05:52.352 align:middle line:84%
and how to deal with it, why
we-- big factors in stress.

00:05:52.352 --> 00:05:53.810 align:middle line:84%
But I want to back
up for a minute,

00:05:53.810 --> 00:05:55.490 align:middle line:84%
because in the beginning I
talked about we are going

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:57.380 align:middle line:84%
to be understanding the
scientific connection

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:58.714 align:middle line:90%
between the heart and the brain.

00:05:58.714 --> 00:05:59.338 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Sure.

00:05:59.338 --> 00:06:00.950 align:middle line:84%
Today we know that
the heart actually

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:04.530 align:middle line:84%
communicates with the brain and
the rest of the body in four

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:05.740 align:middle line:90%
distinct ways.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:07.500 align:middle line:90%
The first way is neurologically.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.590 align:middle line:84%
In your heart and my heart,
and everyone's heart,

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:11.740 align:middle line:84%
there's a complex
nervous system.

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:15.510 align:middle line:84%
It's studied through a field
called neurocardiology.

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:17.999 align:middle line:84%
Those guys actually call
it the brain in the heart.

00:06:17.999 --> 00:06:19.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The brain in the heart?

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:19.790 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: In the heart, yeah.

00:06:19.790 --> 00:06:21.560 align:middle line:84%
So it's a sophisticated
nervous system

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:24.590 align:middle line:84%
found in our heart, communicates
with the big brain in the head.

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:26.720 align:middle line:84%
It does it through
a nerve pathway

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:29.090 align:middle line:84%
that starts in the heart
and travels upward.

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:29.860 align:middle line:90%
I never knew this.

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:31.870 align:middle line:84%
It comes in through the
lower brain centers,

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:33.800 align:middle line:84%
it goes right in through
the limbic system,

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:36.380 align:middle line:84%
which is where the emotional
centers of the brain are.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:38.180 align:middle line:84%
But then, where it
gets interesting

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:40.480 align:middle line:84%
is it terminates all the
way in the neocortex.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.130 align:middle line:84%
The higher perceptual
thinking part of our brain

00:06:43.130 --> 00:06:44.854 align:middle line:84%
is getting information
from our heart.

00:06:44.854 --> 00:06:47.395 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Most think that it goes
from the brain to the heart--

00:06:47.395 --> 00:06:47.980 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Correct.

00:06:47.980 --> 00:06:49.150 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --as opposed
to the opposite, OK.

00:06:49.150 --> 00:06:50.550 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Yeah,
with the information

00:06:50.550 --> 00:06:52.133 align:middle line:84%
going from the brain
down to the heart

00:06:52.133 --> 00:06:54.340 align:middle line:84%
is simply controlling the
timing of the heartbeat.

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:56.070 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

00:06:56.070 --> 00:06:58.440 align:middle line:84%
When you map out neurological
traffic in the body,

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:00.330 align:middle line:84%
it's clearly seen that
the heart is actually

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:02.275 align:middle line:84%
sending a lot more
information to the brain

00:07:02.275 --> 00:07:04.500 align:middle line:84%
than it ever receives
from the brain.

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:07.020 align:middle line:84%
And that's just one way
the heart's communicating.

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:09.650 align:middle line:84%
It does it through something
called a blood pressure wave.

00:07:09.650 --> 00:07:12.060 align:middle line:84%
When we put our hand on our
wrist, we feel their pulse,

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:14.520 align:middle line:84%
it's actually a wave
of energy created

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:16.340 align:middle line:84%
by the squeezing
of the heart that's

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:18.910 align:middle line:84%
pushing the blood
through the body.

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.800 align:middle line:84%
That blood pressure
wave modulates

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:23.550 align:middle line:90%
a lot of the body's systems.

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:25.420 align:middle line:84%
Brain wave activity,
for example,

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:27.910 align:middle line:84%
is synchronized
to changes taking

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:29.300 align:middle line:84%
place in the blood
pressure wave.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.797 align:middle line:84%
That's called a
biophysical communication.

00:07:31.797 --> 00:07:32.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:07:32.630 --> 00:07:34.421 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: There's
another fascinating fact.

00:07:34.421 --> 00:07:36.320 align:middle line:84%
This is another one,
who knew, right?

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:38.660 align:middle line:84%
1983, all the way
back then, the heart

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:43.550 align:middle line:84%
was actually classified as
part of our hormonal system.

00:07:43.550 --> 00:07:44.670 align:middle line:90%
It produces hormones.

00:07:44.670 --> 00:07:45.866 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, interesting.

00:07:45.866 --> 00:07:46.990 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Nobody knew this.

00:07:46.990 --> 00:07:50.269 align:middle line:84%
So there's hormones like
atrial peptide and oxytocin

00:07:50.269 --> 00:07:51.810 align:middle line:84%
that are being
produced by the heart.

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:52.768 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: From the heart?

00:07:52.768 --> 00:07:54.940 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: So there's a
biochemical conversation

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:56.570 align:middle line:90%
happening as well.

00:07:56.570 --> 00:08:00.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, these freeways, Lisa,
are all biological-- hardwired

00:08:00.010 --> 00:08:01.940 align:middle line:90%
biological processes.

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:03.940 align:middle line:84%
Definitively, without
a doubt showing

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:06.060 align:middle line:84%
that the heart is doing
more than pumping blood.

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:10.410 align:middle line:84%
But where it gets interesting
for me is the fourth way.

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:11.860 align:middle line:84%
Our hearts are
electrical organs.

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:15.386 align:middle line:84%
They're energy-producing
organ in our body.

00:08:15.386 --> 00:08:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
a doctor measures

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:20.187 align:middle line:84%
is that energy, when
we get our ECG or EKG.

00:08:20.187 --> 00:08:21.770 align:middle line:84%
They're measuring
an electrical signal

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:24.340 align:middle line:84%
being produced by the
beating of the heart.

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:27.330 align:middle line:90%
Now, that signal is strong.

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:29.980 align:middle line:84%
It's the strongest source of
bioelectricity in our body,

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:33.530 align:middle line:84%
40 to 60 times stronger than
the second most powerful source,

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:34.412 align:middle line:90%
which is the brain.

00:08:34.412 --> 00:08:35.197 align:middle line:90%
40 to 60 times.

00:08:35.197 --> 00:08:36.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Interesting,
so it is actually

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:38.890 align:middle line:84%
emitting a stronger
signal than the brain.

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:39.809 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: 40 to
60 times stronger.

00:08:39.809 --> 00:08:41.142 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: 40 to 60 times stronger.

00:08:41.142 --> 00:08:43.419 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Now, that signal--
the electrical energy

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:46.300 align:middle line:84%
from that signal goes to
every single cell in our body,

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:49.240 align:middle line:84%
and it permeates
every single cell.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:50.630 align:middle line:84%
Here's where it
gets interesting.

00:08:50.630 --> 00:08:53.780 align:middle line:84%
It creates an electromagnetic
field of energy

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:56.010 align:middle line:90%
that surrounds you and me--

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:57.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The body?

00:08:57.590 --> 00:09:00.270 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --in 360 degrees,
extending beyond the skin

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:02.140 align:middle line:90%
out into space.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:03.992 align:middle line:84%
In the book "The
HeartMath Solution"

00:09:03.992 --> 00:09:05.450 align:middle line:84%
that I had the
privilege of writing

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:07.400 align:middle line:84%
with Doc Childre, the
HeartMath founder,

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:09.321 align:middle line:84%
we reported on another
clinic's finding

00:09:09.321 --> 00:09:11.820 align:middle line:84%
that said they measured it 8
to 10 feet outside of the body.

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:12.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:14.378 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Our researchers
say they can reliably

00:09:14.378 --> 00:09:16.930 align:middle line:90%
stand behind 3 to 4 feet.

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:18.056 align:middle line:90%
So we have these fields.

00:09:18.056 --> 00:09:19.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How do you measure?

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:20.937 align:middle line:84%
So our body has an
electrical system

00:09:20.937 --> 00:09:23.270 align:middle line:84%
and it's going through the 3
trillion cells in the body,

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:26.860 align:middle line:84%
and then that emanates out into
something called a human energy

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:27.360 align:middle line:90%
field?

00:09:27.360 --> 00:09:27.990 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: It's energy field.

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:29.500 align:middle line:84%
It's not an aura; it's
not subtle energy.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.980 align:middle line:84%
It's electromagnetic energy
we're measuring in this case.

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:34.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so if somebody
walks in the room who is angry,

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:38.900 align:middle line:84%
and you feel that,
it's an actual field?

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:40.755 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: That's one
possible explanation.

00:09:40.755 --> 00:09:41.870 align:middle line:90%
The field changes.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:43.510 align:middle line:84%
First of all, the
field goes-- it's

00:09:43.510 --> 00:09:46.420 align:middle line:84%
radiating out or
broadcasting out.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:48.660 align:middle line:84%
The energy in the field,
the frequency, so to speak,

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:50.076 align:middle line:84%
in the field will
change depending

00:09:50.076 --> 00:09:52.089 align:middle line:84%
upon what emotional
state we're in.

00:09:52.089 --> 00:09:53.630 align:middle line:84%
If you're feeling
anger, for example,

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:55.849 align:middle line:84%
or frustrated, or
nervous, or whatever;

00:09:55.849 --> 00:09:58.390 align:middle line:84%
it's usually producing what's
called an incoherent spectrum--

00:09:58.390 --> 00:10:01.800 align:middle line:84%
a lot of frequencies
inharmoniously trying

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:03.860 align:middle line:90%
to exist in the same place.

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:04.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.720 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: When we switch
the emotional state

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:10.550 align:middle line:84%
and we begin to feel emotions
that are associated with heart,

00:10:10.550 --> 00:10:14.160 align:middle line:84%
like, let's say, deep care for
someone or something or love,

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:16.830 align:middle line:84%
or appreciation for,
hey, life is good,

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.170 align:middle line:84%
that field will change
and becomes more ordered.

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:21.490 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
coherent spectrum.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:25.640 align:middle line:84%
And so we are literally
broadcasting our emotions out

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:27.240 align:middle line:90%
in the space through this field.

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the anger
and the frustration

00:10:29.570 --> 00:10:32.190 align:middle line:84%
is more of a frenetic; the
love, the appreciation,

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:34.750 align:middle line:90%
the gratitude is more coherent?

00:10:34.750 --> 00:10:36.940 align:middle line:84%
And that's the field
that literally you feel?

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:38.530 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Yeah, so we may
feel that from someone.

00:10:38.530 --> 00:10:39.240 align:middle line:90%
That's one explanation--

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:39.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:10:39.530 --> 00:10:41.529 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --for why are
we can walk into a room,

00:10:41.529 --> 00:10:43.300 align:middle line:84%
we see two people,
they look normal,

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:46.180 align:middle line:84%
but yet we don't feel
that something's right.

00:10:46.180 --> 00:10:48.106 align:middle line:84%
And we ask them if
there's anything going on,

00:10:48.106 --> 00:10:50.480 align:middle line:84%
we find out they've been having
an argument, for example.

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:51.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:53.328 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: This not saying
scientifically definitively

00:10:53.328 --> 00:10:55.310 align:middle line:84%
that that's why
we understand it,

00:10:55.310 --> 00:10:58.305 align:middle line:84%
but it's one way we may
be able to explain it.

00:10:58.305 --> 00:10:59.450 align:middle line:90%
Here's why.

00:10:59.450 --> 00:11:02.820 align:middle line:84%
When we go to this understanding
of heart communication,

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:06.195 align:middle line:84%
now we're out of just biology,
now we're into physics.

00:11:06.195 --> 00:11:07.320 align:middle line:90%
We're in the energy fields.

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:10.140 align:middle line:84%
How does this field relate
to the field in our brain?

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:11.567 align:middle line:84%
How does my field
and your field,

00:11:11.567 --> 00:11:13.400 align:middle line:84%
how are our fields
relating to one another--

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:14.149 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right now.

00:11:14.149 --> 00:11:15.110 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: --right now.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:17.510 align:middle line:84%
And then where we've
gone with it now

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:20.880 align:middle line:84%
and where we'll talk about
some more in our dialogue today

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:24.040 align:middle line:84%
is how does the field produced
by my heart and the field

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:27.310 align:middle line:84%
collectively of humanity
relate to one another?

00:11:27.310 --> 00:11:29.710 align:middle line:84%
And then how do those fields
relate to the energy fields

00:11:29.710 --> 00:11:31.640 align:middle line:84%
produced by the
planet, the Earth

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:33.740 align:middle line:84%
itself, that whole
energetic connection.

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:35.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The micro
to the macro, yes.

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:36.240 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Exactly.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:37.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it goes
beyond what you

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:39.670 align:middle line:84%
see when you get on a treadmill
and you put your little thumb

00:11:39.670 --> 00:11:40.905 align:middle line:84%
in the thing, and you
see your heart rate

00:11:40.905 --> 00:11:43.229 align:middle line:84%
and how fast it's beating
when you're on the treadmill,

00:11:43.229 --> 00:11:43.770 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:11:43.770 --> 00:11:48.360 align:middle line:84%
It goes beyond what the
doctor shows you in an EKG.

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:53.810 align:middle line:84%
It goes beyond all of those
just parts of evidence.

00:11:53.810 --> 00:11:57.520 align:middle line:84%
This is something that goes
into the human energy field

00:11:57.520 --> 00:11:59.820 align:middle line:84%
and it's centered in the
heart and sends a message

00:11:59.820 --> 00:12:00.650 align:middle line:90%
to the brain.

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:03.107 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: It becomes a really
interesting thought process

00:12:03.107 --> 00:12:05.440 align:middle line:84%
of how do we relate as human
beings to something larger.

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:09.590 align:middle line:84%
And the heart is playing the
central role in all of that.

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:12.525 align:middle line:84%
And I think what's important
is that heart and brain are not

00:12:12.525 --> 00:12:14.320 align:middle line:84%
in competition;
they work together.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:16.250 align:middle line:90%
It's a hard-wired system.

00:12:16.250 --> 00:12:22.390 align:middle line:84%
But we've somehow believed
that all intelligence is only

00:12:22.390 --> 00:12:24.397 align:middle line:90%
happening in our brain.

00:12:24.397 --> 00:12:26.105 align:middle line:84%
And what I believe
from my own experience

00:12:26.105 --> 00:12:29.900 align:middle line:84%
is that the brain is a master
interpreter of information,

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:32.840 align:middle line:84%
that it sorts, compares,
compartmentalizes,

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:35.530 align:middle line:84%
tries to make sense out of
information that it receives.

00:12:35.530 --> 00:12:38.615 align:middle line:84%
But is not the only source of
where we get intelligence from.

00:12:38.615 --> 00:12:41.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Let's talk about some of
the specific causes of stress.

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:44.894 align:middle line:84%
You mentioned to me that
there's two causes of stress.

00:12:44.894 --> 00:12:46.310 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Most of
the surveys show

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:48.430 align:middle line:84%
that either number
one or number two

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:50.690 align:middle line:84%
is going to be one
of these two things.

00:12:50.690 --> 00:12:53.114 align:middle line:84%
One is the feeling of
not having enough time.

00:12:53.114 --> 00:12:55.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The feeling of
not having enough time?

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:55.940 align:middle line:90%
Constantly being rushed?

00:12:55.940 --> 00:12:56.410 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Yeah.

00:12:56.410 --> 00:12:57.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you think
any of that's brought

00:12:57.270 --> 00:12:59.750 align:middle line:84%
on by the information and
the technology age, and--

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:01.090 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Absolutely, yeah.

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:04.027 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I mean everything is
so instantaneous and designed

00:13:04.027 --> 00:13:06.360 align:middle line:84%
to be more convenient, more
convenient, more convenient,

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.200 align:middle line:90%
so you can do more in less time.

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:10.870 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Yeah, we're actually
getting more information

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:12.500 align:middle line:90%
than we were designed to get.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.000 align:middle line:84%
Our physiology hasn't
even caught up yet

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.025 align:middle line:84%
with being able to absorb
that much information.

00:13:17.025 --> 00:13:17.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:19.760 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: And we stay dialed
in and wired and connected

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:20.930 align:middle line:90%
to everything all the time--

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:21.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Constantly.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:22.416 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --and
that's part of it,

00:13:22.416 --> 00:13:24.490 align:middle line:84%
certainly, the feeling
of not have enough time.

00:13:24.490 --> 00:13:27.710 align:middle line:84%
But we also-- time is
actually, in a sense,

00:13:27.710 --> 00:13:28.910 align:middle line:90%
speeding up as well.

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:33.540 align:middle line:84%
More events are happening in a
space of time than ever before.

00:13:33.540 --> 00:13:36.802 align:middle line:84%
So the feeling that people
are having about not

00:13:36.802 --> 00:13:39.010 align:middle line:84%
having enough time or about
the overwhelm of it all--

00:13:39.010 --> 00:13:40.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Is that documented?

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:42.325 align:middle line:90%
Is that really documented?

00:13:42.325 --> 00:13:44.700 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: I don't know if it'd
be documented in a totally

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:46.760 align:middle line:84%
empirical way, but,
certainly, I think,

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:49.307 align:middle line:84%
if you step back and
think about your own life,

00:13:49.307 --> 00:13:50.390 align:middle line:90%
are more things happening?

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:53.790 align:middle line:84%
Do you feel more things going
on than you ever have, right?

00:13:53.790 --> 00:13:56.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Absolutely, but I
don't know if it's just me

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.540 align:middle line:84%
or if it's just what
people are talking about.

00:13:58.540 --> 00:13:59.130 align:middle line:90%
Is it really--

00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:00.880 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, it's
pretty much universal

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:04.390 align:middle line:84%
in my experience of asking
people what they feel and about

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:06.710 align:middle line:84%
do they feel like things are
speeding up in their life.

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:09.110 align:middle line:84%
Now, I've played with that
in some of my experiments.

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:11.530 align:middle line:84%
I might be in a cab with
a cabdriver taking me

00:14:11.530 --> 00:14:13.310 align:middle line:84%
from the airport and
I'll say, do you ever

00:14:13.310 --> 00:14:15.890 align:middle line:84%
think your life's getting
faster than it was before?

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:19.180 align:middle line:84%
And I get 100% yes
back every time

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:20.472 align:middle line:90%
when I ask questions like that.

00:14:20.472 --> 00:14:21.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I'm not
sure you could ever

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:23.690 align:middle line:84%
quantify that and
double-blind study it.

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:24.890 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: I don't know if
we need to quantify it.

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:25.150 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Review it.

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:26.530 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: People are
actually experiencing

00:14:26.530 --> 00:14:27.587 align:middle line:90%
that in their own life.

00:14:27.587 --> 00:14:29.420 align:middle line:84%
It's that feeling of
not having enough time,

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:32.520 align:middle line:84%
too much to do, not enough time,
the overwhelmed feeling that's

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:34.840 align:middle line:84%
one of the primary causes of
stress, usually number one

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:36.670 align:middle line:90%
or two in a stress survey.

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:41.797 align:middle line:84%
The second cause is feeling
that you're not in control.

00:14:41.797 --> 00:14:43.130 align:middle line:90%
And that's a person, let's say--

00:14:43.130 --> 00:14:43.760 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you
don't have choice.

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:44.380 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: You don't have choice.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:44.964 align:middle line:90%
You're in job.

00:14:44.964 --> 00:14:46.255 align:middle line:90%
Your boss tells you what to do.

00:14:46.255 --> 00:14:47.010 align:middle line:90%
You have to do it.

00:14:47.010 --> 00:14:48.400 align:middle line:90%
You can't do anything about it.

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:51.360 align:middle line:84%
That's a feeling that creates
a tremendous amount of stress.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:54.310 align:middle line:84%
You're locked into situations in
life that you can't get out of.

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.445 align:middle line:90%
You're doomed.

00:14:56.445 --> 00:14:57.500 align:middle line:90%
You have no choice.

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:00.470 align:middle line:84%
You're going through these
feelings of resignation

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:03.670 align:middle line:84%
and disappointment that leads to
these very stressful feelings--

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:06.390 align:middle line:84%
they're sadness and depression
feelings, and things like that.

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:08.150 align:middle line:84%
They're all part of
what stress really is.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:09.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Interesting,
right, of course.

00:15:09.310 --> 00:15:11.309 align:middle line:84%
And then the cardiologists
will always tell you,

00:15:11.309 --> 00:15:12.704 align:middle line:90%
you need to reduce your stress.

00:15:12.704 --> 00:15:13.370 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Right.

00:15:13.370 --> 00:15:13.780 align:middle line:90%
Easier said than done.

00:15:13.780 --> 00:15:14.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And change your diet.

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:16.330 align:middle line:84%
So this can all be fixed
through stress and diet.

00:15:16.330 --> 00:15:17.980 align:middle line:84%
And you walk out of there
going stress and diet, what

00:15:17.980 --> 00:15:18.500 align:middle line:90%
do I do about that?

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:19.540 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Exactly, yeah.

00:15:19.540 --> 00:15:21.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So exactly how
do you reduce the stress?

00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:23.300 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, that's
where HeartMath comes in.

00:15:23.300 --> 00:15:25.610 align:middle line:84%
And we do lots of different
kinds of training programs,

00:15:25.610 --> 00:15:27.840 align:middle line:84%
resilience-based training,
performance improvement

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:30.480 align:middle line:84%
training, personal growth
training through our Heart

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:31.720 align:middle line:90%
Mastery program that we have.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:33.370 align:middle line:84%
A lot of things
that we do in there.

00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:36.226 align:middle line:84%
Stress is usually somewhere
in that training process

00:15:36.226 --> 00:15:37.600 align:middle line:84%
to begin to look
at that and deal

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:39.570 align:middle line:84%
with it, because,
again, we want to be

00:15:39.570 --> 00:15:42.460 align:middle line:84%
able to remove some the things
that stand in our way of having

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:44.300 align:middle line:84%
these fulfilling
and meaningful lives

00:15:44.300 --> 00:15:46.400 align:middle line:84%
and contributing to this
change we're experiencing

00:15:46.400 --> 00:15:49.310 align:middle line:90%
in the world in a dynamic way.

00:15:49.310 --> 00:15:50.930 align:middle line:90%
We have to get the blocks out.

00:15:50.930 --> 00:15:52.921 align:middle line:90%
So we do focus on that some.

00:15:52.921 --> 00:15:54.420 align:middle line:84%
But see, there's a
state that we can

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:57.440 align:middle line:84%
enter into that's measurable
by looking at heart,

00:15:57.440 --> 00:16:00.440 align:middle line:84%
again, that sort
of offsets stress

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:03.660 align:middle line:84%
could be looked at almost in a
way as an antidote to stress.

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:06.320 align:middle line:84%
And it's a state
called coherence.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:10.270 align:middle line:84%
There's a medical term for it--
psychophysiological coherence.

00:16:10.270 --> 00:16:12.140 align:middle line:84%
That's a mouthful for
a southerner to say,

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:15.100 align:middle line:90%
but it's a long word.

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.570 align:middle line:90%
Psychophysiological coherence.

00:16:17.570 --> 00:16:21.670 align:middle line:84%
And coherence is a
highly-ordered state

00:16:21.670 --> 00:16:23.860 align:middle line:84%
physiologically, when
all of our body systems

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:25.670 align:middle line:90%
are working together.

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:27.860 align:middle line:84%
They are synchronizing
to changes in our heart.

00:16:27.860 --> 00:16:29.530 align:middle line:84%
If you think about
the heart, it's

00:16:29.530 --> 00:16:31.530 align:middle line:84%
the master rhythm
maker in the body.

00:16:31.530 --> 00:16:34.130 align:middle line:84%
It's setting the tempo; it's
setting the tone for everything

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:35.920 align:middle line:90%
that's happening internally.

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:39.570 align:middle line:84%
All the other system synchronize
to heart-- respiration,

00:16:39.570 --> 00:16:41.980 align:middle line:84%
digestion, hormonal response,
immune system response--

00:16:41.980 --> 00:16:42.940 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Blood pressure.

00:16:42.940 --> 00:16:44.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: All triggering
off our heart, right?

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:47.870 align:middle line:84%
So when you're in
the coherence state,

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.130 align:middle line:84%
the rhythmic beating
patterns of the heart,

00:16:50.130 --> 00:16:53.140 align:middle line:84%
which we call heart rhythms,
become very nice and ordered.

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:56.680 align:middle line:84%
There's a synchronization in the
rhythmic beating of the heart.

00:16:56.680 --> 00:16:58.860 align:middle line:84%
All the other systems are
synchronizing to that,

00:16:58.860 --> 00:17:01.960 align:middle line:84%
and you have this very
efficient physiological state,

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:03.592 align:middle line:84%
where less energy
is being wasted.

00:17:03.592 --> 00:17:06.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is something we're
going to see later is these

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:06.549 align:middle line:90%
actual--

00:17:06.549 --> 00:17:08.160 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: We'll see that, yeah.

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:10.060 align:middle line:84%
But it's also
psychophysiological,

00:17:10.060 --> 00:17:12.819 align:middle line:84%
which means there's a
psychological component.

00:17:12.819 --> 00:17:17.650 align:middle line:84%
Coherence is often triggered
by feeling positive emotions.

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:20.040 align:middle line:84%
And they're the ones
associated with heart.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:22.569 align:middle line:84%
When we're feeling care
or love or compassion,

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:24.771 align:middle line:84%
we generally have
an opportunity to be

00:17:24.771 --> 00:17:26.020 align:middle line:90%
triggering the coherent state.

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:27.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it goes
back to feeling?

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:28.363 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Back to feeling.

00:17:28.363 --> 00:17:31.140 align:middle line:84%
And once we're in the coherent
state, then those emotions,

00:17:31.140 --> 00:17:35.910 align:middle line:84%
those kind of emotions
become much easier to feel.

00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:39.192 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So to come up with
that feeling yourself?

00:17:39.192 --> 00:17:40.900 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: To generate
it from the inside.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:41.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To generate
it from the inside.

00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:43.930 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: And as-- we'll go
through techniques as we go

00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:46.540 align:middle line:84%
through our dialogue today,
you'll-- we'll give people ways

00:17:46.540 --> 00:17:50.080 align:middle line:84%
in which it can help them do
that using associative memory

00:17:50.080 --> 00:17:52.890 align:middle line:84%
and things to trigger
emotional responses that are

00:17:52.890 --> 00:17:54.210 align:middle line:90%
regenerative.

00:17:54.210 --> 00:17:57.400 align:middle line:84%
But all this adds up to you can
measure this whole thing that's

00:17:57.400 --> 00:17:58.810 align:middle line:90%
going on in the body.

00:17:58.810 --> 00:18:02.374 align:middle line:84%
You do it through
looking at heart rhythms.

00:18:02.374 --> 00:18:04.540 align:middle line:84%
Heart rhythms, there's a
medical term for that, too.

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:08.500 align:middle line:84%
It's called heart rate
variability analysis-- HRV.

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:09.285 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: HRV, OK.

00:18:09.285 --> 00:18:11.660 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: What that's measuring
is not just a heart rate,

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:14.290 align:middle line:84%
like you get on a pulse
monitor on a piece of exercise

00:18:14.290 --> 00:18:17.940 align:middle line:84%
equipment that's telling you
75 beats a minute or whatever.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:19.710 align:middle line:84%
If we go to a doctor,
and the doctor says,

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:22.100 align:middle line:84%
Lisa, your heart rate
is 75 beats a minute,

00:18:22.100 --> 00:18:26.310 align:middle line:84%
what that doctor actually told
you was that's an average.

00:18:26.310 --> 00:18:28.300 align:middle line:90%
An average is 75 beats a minute.

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:30.630 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't beating at 75
beats for the minute.

00:18:30.630 --> 00:18:31.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, right, my average.

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:34.170 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Yeah, so the
timing between each heartbeat

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:37.330 align:middle line:84%
is actually subtly changing
between every single heart

00:18:37.330 --> 00:18:38.160 align:middle line:90%
beat.

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And when you analyze
those subtle changes,

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:43.182 align:middle line:84%
you're doing heart rate
variability analyses.

00:18:43.182 --> 00:18:45.390 align:middle line:84%
So you're measuring the
variability that's happening,

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:48.940 align:middle line:84%
not just the
standard heart rate.

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:51.430 align:middle line:84%
We want a lot of variability,
that's a sign of health.

00:18:51.430 --> 00:18:54.260 align:middle line:84%
We want a wide range of
speeds at which our heart can

00:18:54.260 --> 00:18:57.290 align:middle line:84%
pump and do its
cardiovascular job.

00:18:57.290 --> 00:19:01.400 align:middle line:84%
We also want to have some
ability to modulate or control

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.230 align:middle line:84%
those heart rhythms,
so that rather

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:07.510 align:middle line:84%
than them being chaotic and
irregular, they are more smooth

00:19:07.510 --> 00:19:09.430 align:middle line:90%
and ordered.

00:19:09.430 --> 00:19:10.880 align:middle line:84%
Many things affect
heart rhythms.

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:12.400 align:middle line:84%
Movement, right
now our speech is

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.108 align:middle line:84%
going to make them
jagged to some degree,

00:19:14.108 --> 00:19:15.661 align:middle line:90%
because the heart is having to--

00:19:15.661 --> 00:19:16.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, so movement.

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:20.100 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Listen,
it's fine, but emotion

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:22.610 align:middle line:84%
triggers lots of changes
in our heart rhythms.

00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:25.480 align:middle line:84%
And researchers didn't know
this until our scientists

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:28.400 align:middle line:84%
at the Institute of HeartMath
began to uncover these things.

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:31.610 align:middle line:84%
They really hadn't studied it
from the emotional perspective.

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:35.270 align:middle line:84%
So what your viewers are
seeing now on the screen

00:19:35.270 --> 00:19:38.462 align:middle line:84%
are heart rate
variability analysis data.

00:19:38.462 --> 00:19:40.170 align:middle line:84%
In the top view of
that graph-- and we're

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:42.690 align:middle line:84%
looking at 200 seconds
of time on each graph--

00:19:42.690 --> 00:19:45.550 align:middle line:84%
you see a very jagged
and irregular pattern.

00:19:45.550 --> 00:19:48.430 align:middle line:84%
And that is a person that is
not moving, they're not talking,

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:51.240 align:middle line:84%
there's no reason for it
to be jagged and irregular,

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:53.242 align:middle line:84%
but they are feeling a
feeling of frustration.

00:19:53.242 --> 00:19:54.700 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, they're
not moving, OK.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:56.580 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: In the
experiment, we just said,

00:19:56.580 --> 00:19:58.788 align:middle line:84%
think about something that
makes you feel frustrated.

00:19:58.788 --> 00:20:01.410 align:middle line:84%
And what you see is a lot of
timing changes happening in

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:04.695 align:middle line:84%
over a short time span,
speeding up and slowing down,

00:20:04.695 --> 00:20:06.210 align:middle line:84%
and speeding up
and slowing down.

00:20:06.210 --> 00:20:07.794 align:middle line:84%
And this kind of
pattern is happening.

00:20:07.794 --> 00:20:08.834 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's irregular.

00:20:08.834 --> 00:20:11.250 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: It's sending
signals through the body that

00:20:11.250 --> 00:20:13.810 align:middle line:84%
cascade, like up into
the brain, for example.

00:20:13.810 --> 00:20:16.930 align:middle line:84%
And when those signals get
into the brain or cascade

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:18.810 align:middle line:84%
in the brain, it
creates a condition

00:20:18.810 --> 00:20:22.635 align:middle line:90%
called cortical inhibition.

00:20:22.635 --> 00:20:25.440 align:middle line:84%
The higher perceptual
centers are less active.

00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:28.040 align:middle line:84%
They begin to shut down, so
we don't think as clearly.

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:29.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So we're not as smart.

00:20:29.350 --> 00:20:31.230 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: And we can even
have reaction things going,

00:20:31.230 --> 00:20:32.590 align:middle line:90%
like we knock something over--

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:33.381 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah, clumsy.

00:20:33.381 --> 00:20:36.090 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --whatever, we don't
even have full-brain capacity.

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:38.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, in the bottom
view on that graph,

00:20:38.390 --> 00:20:41.660 align:middle line:84%
we see this pretty
sine wave-like pattern.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:46.260 align:middle line:84%
This is actually the same
person a few minutes later.

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:50.820 align:middle line:84%
But now we've asked them to feel
the feeling of appreciation,

00:20:50.820 --> 00:20:52.700 align:middle line:84%
appreciate something
in your life.

00:20:52.700 --> 00:20:54.600 align:middle line:84%
So they're shifting
from feeling frustrated

00:20:54.600 --> 00:20:56.350 align:middle line:90%
to feeling appreciative.

00:20:56.350 --> 00:20:58.650 align:middle line:84%
And the heart rhythms
respond accordingly

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:01.780 align:middle line:84%
to the change they made
in their emotional state.

00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:03.760 align:middle line:84%
When you have the sine
wave-like pattern,

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:07.080 align:middle line:84%
that is what coherence
looks like in the body.

00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:08.790 align:middle line:84%
Coherence is this
highly-ordered state.

00:21:08.790 --> 00:21:10.248 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of like
being in the flow

00:21:10.248 --> 00:21:12.390 align:middle line:84%
or being in the zone,
an athlete in the zone.

00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:13.800 align:middle line:90%
It's a very aware state.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:16.620 align:middle line:84%
It's not a sleepy-time,
just relaxed state.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:20.260 align:middle line:84%
It's a state where you are
operating really at your best.

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:22.740 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the antidote
to stress is coherence?

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:23.490 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Correct.

00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:25.320 align:middle line:84%
And you can measure
coherence by looking

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:28.890 align:middle line:90%
at changes in our heart rhythms.

00:21:28.890 --> 00:21:32.832 align:middle line:84%
Coherence and stress can't
live in the same room.

00:21:32.832 --> 00:21:34.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Law of physics, yeah.

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:35.748 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Coherence
will move stress out.

00:21:35.748 --> 00:21:37.490 align:middle line:84%
So we learn to
shift these emotions

00:21:37.490 --> 00:21:39.323 align:middle line:84%
and learn to get more
in the coherent state,

00:21:39.323 --> 00:21:41.470 align:middle line:84%
then we can better
manage our stress.

00:21:41.470 --> 00:21:43.730 align:middle line:84%
And there's great
benefit in that.

00:21:43.730 --> 00:21:45.420 align:middle line:84%
We can improve our
health that way,

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:47.590 align:middle line:84%
we can certainly perform better
in life, we communicate better.

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:49.423 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Better
relationships, yeah, overall.

00:21:49.423 --> 00:21:50.350 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: You got it.

00:21:50.350 --> 00:21:52.660 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So now, how does
that experience with us

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:57.180 align:middle line:84%
physiologically affect
the, as you said earlier,

00:21:57.180 --> 00:22:01.190 align:middle line:84%
the environment and then,
ultimately, affect the planet?

00:22:01.190 --> 00:22:04.190 align:middle line:84%
How does that-- how
does one little person?

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:07.610 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, certainly,
as one little person,

00:22:07.610 --> 00:22:09.474 align:middle line:84%
we are still putting
out an energy

00:22:09.474 --> 00:22:11.140 align:middle line:84%
that's contributing
to the consciousness

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:12.360 align:middle line:90%
climate of the planet.

00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:13.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Consciousness climate?

00:22:13.710 --> 00:22:15.650 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: That's what I
like to call it, yeah.

00:22:15.650 --> 00:22:17.850 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we live
in a field of energy

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:19.660 align:middle line:90%
that's reflecting back to us.

00:22:19.660 --> 00:22:21.260 align:middle line:84%
Not just what we
think in our minds,

00:22:21.260 --> 00:22:22.420 align:middle line:90%
but what we feel in our hearts.

00:22:22.420 --> 00:22:24.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Constantly around
us, there's fields of energy.

00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:25.480 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: All the time.

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:26.690 align:middle line:90%
And we have our own field.

00:22:26.690 --> 00:22:28.152 align:middle line:90%
We produce our own field.

00:22:28.152 --> 00:22:30.485 align:middle line:84%
And it's measurable through
that one type of measurement

00:22:30.485 --> 00:22:32.740 align:middle line:84%
that we talked about
earlier, but there's

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:35.880 align:middle line:84%
more fields and more fields
that we're producing ourself.

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:39.050 align:middle line:84%
So we are creating our own
field environment all the time.

00:22:39.050 --> 00:22:41.320 align:middle line:84%
And what feeds that
field environment?

00:22:41.320 --> 00:22:42.480 align:middle line:90%
Our emotions.

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:44.140 align:middle line:84%
Our emotions are
changing the energy

00:22:44.140 --> 00:22:45.640 align:middle line:90%
that goes into the field.

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:47.580 align:middle line:84%
And that energy's
going out from us.

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So we're affecting
it, the external situation

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:50.949 align:middle line:90%
is not affecting us?

00:22:50.949 --> 00:22:52.990 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, internal
situation can affect us,

00:22:52.990 --> 00:22:54.130 align:middle line:90%
but we also affect it.

00:22:54.130 --> 00:22:55.510 align:middle line:84%
There's a relationship
between the two.

00:22:55.510 --> 00:22:57.343 align:middle line:84%
And we have more conscious
control over that

00:22:57.343 --> 00:22:59.090 align:middle line:90%
than we've ever realized before.

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:02.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So, OK, for example,
a friend of mine cannot stand

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:03.610 align:middle line:90%
going through airport security.

00:23:03.610 --> 00:23:05.160 align:middle line:84%
Feels like she
doesn't have choice,

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:06.910 align:middle line:84%
feels like she
doesn't have control.

00:23:06.910 --> 00:23:11.740 align:middle line:84%
So she goes to the situation
with anxiety around that.

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:14.682 align:middle line:84%
Now, in her mind,
it's that situation

00:23:14.682 --> 00:23:17.015 align:middle line:84%
that's causing her the stress,
because beforehand she'll

00:23:17.015 --> 00:23:17.740 align:middle line:90%
be fine.

00:23:17.740 --> 00:23:19.950 align:middle line:84%
And then she goes up
to that situation,

00:23:19.950 --> 00:23:21.830 align:middle line:84%
and I see her body
start to tense up,

00:23:21.830 --> 00:23:24.060 align:middle line:84%
and I see the
experience, and then

00:23:24.060 --> 00:23:27.000 align:middle line:84%
she starts to get into an
altercation with a TSA member,

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.290 align:middle line:84%
and then it goes on
from there, it cascades.

00:23:29.290 --> 00:23:31.460 align:middle line:84%
So how are you saying
that's coming from her?

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:33.310 align:middle line:84%
It's coming from
the environment.

00:23:33.310 --> 00:23:35.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, she can control
one thing in that situation.

00:23:35.810 --> 00:23:37.480 align:middle line:84%
She can't control,
like you said,

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:39.260 align:middle line:84%
the process of having
to go through that

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:40.187 align:middle line:90%
to get on an airplane.

00:23:40.187 --> 00:23:40.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:23:40.770 --> 00:23:41.695 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: She can't stop that.

00:23:41.695 --> 00:23:41.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:43.700 align:middle line:84%
If she wants to get
on the airplane.

00:23:43.700 --> 00:23:44.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: If she wants
to get on the airplane,

00:23:44.810 --> 00:23:45.650 align:middle line:90%
that's what she's got to do.

00:23:45.650 --> 00:23:47.090 align:middle line:84%
So she has one
choice, and that's

00:23:47.090 --> 00:23:49.090 align:middle line:84%
her internal reaction
to that situation.

00:23:49.090 --> 00:23:50.420 align:middle line:90%
She can control that.

00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:53.079 align:middle line:84%
Just like-- I'll use another
example-- a traffic jam.

00:23:53.079 --> 00:23:55.120 align:middle line:84%
We can't control we're in
the traffic jam, right?

00:23:55.120 --> 00:23:56.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Right, OK,
that's a good one.

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:57.380 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Now, what
are going to do?

00:23:57.380 --> 00:23:59.210 align:middle line:84%
We can only control
our reaction to it.

00:23:59.210 --> 00:24:01.740 align:middle line:84%
Now, we can either let that
traffic jam or that TSA

00:24:01.740 --> 00:24:04.430 align:middle line:84%
experience, the
screening experience,

00:24:04.430 --> 00:24:09.170 align:middle line:84%
be stressful and to
debilitate us in certain ways,

00:24:09.170 --> 00:24:11.576 align:middle line:84%
and certainly rob us of
energy as we go through it.

00:24:11.576 --> 00:24:12.950 align:middle line:84%
Or we can make a
conscious choice

00:24:12.950 --> 00:24:14.658 align:middle line:84%
to begin to shift that
perspective on it.

00:24:14.658 --> 00:24:17.790 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't mean we have to like
either one of them necessarily.

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:20.920 align:middle line:84%
We can get to a place--
a more neutral place,

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:22.930 align:middle line:84%
to where we're not
draining as much energy,

00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:26.360 align:middle line:84%
to where we are more
accepting of that,

00:24:26.360 --> 00:24:28.700 align:middle line:84%
more allowing of what
we have to go through.

00:24:28.700 --> 00:24:31.330 align:middle line:84%
And in doing that, that's a
perfect example, actually,

00:24:31.330 --> 00:24:34.400 align:middle line:84%
